In the end, the asbestos ban was upheld in six key areas:Â  corrugated paper, roll board, commercial paper, specialty paper, flooring felt, and new uses of asbestos

text: The EPA, under the leadership of Pruitt, published the rule on June 11, 2018 reversing the ban on new uses of asbestos. It states, âThe proposed significant new use of asbestos (including as part of an article) is manufacturing (including importing) or processing for certain uses identified by EPA.âÂ  Essentially, that means companies could get EPA approval for the use of asbestos in new applications.

text: The Pedro Pan program enabled parents to send their children to the U.S. as a last resort to avoid communist indoctrination. Operated by the Archdiocese of Miami and the U.S. State DepartmentÂ  from 1960 to 1962, the program brought a total of 14,000 unaccompanied Cuban minors to the U.S., the Cold War Museum reports:

label: None
text: Operation Pedro Pan lasted for 22 months, then it was shut down. It ceased existence in 1962 as a result of the Cuban Missile Crisis. The crisis put a freeze on any commercial air service between Havana, Cuba and Miami, Florida.Â  After its termination, children that remained in the country either stayed with relatives, orphanages, or foster homes until their family successfully made it out of Cuba. The duration of time that the âPedro Pansâ waited for their parents varied: sometimes it took days, weeks, or months. But for the very unfortunate, it took years for their family to come, since Castro made it so increasingly difficult for Anti-Cubans to leave or even live freely in his nation.

text: The situation drew plenty of attention â and it fueled a backlash against Red Hen owner Stephanie Wilkinson that resembles baseless âPizza Gateâ claims about Hillary Clinton taking part in a child sex trafficking. text: State business records list Stephanie Wilkinson as the sole owner of the Red Hen. Of course, the rumor conveniently claims that the registered sex offender is a âsilent partner.â That means itâs impossible to verify the claim.

text: It should also be noted that Barney Allen Frazierâs mugshot and sex offender registry information is publicly available online. And, when typing âregistered sex offenders in Lexingtonâ into a Google search, Frazierâs information is the first to pop up on the leading search result. It could be a coincidence, but it could also be a sign that someone Google searched for sex offenders in Lexington to use in a false rumor.

text: Bill Clintonâs 1996 Immigration Law is to Blame for Child Separations-Fiction!

label: Claim
text: Bill Clintonâs 1996 (or 1997) immigration law is to blame for a federal policy that separates immigrant children from their parents at the border.

label: Credibility
text: Bill Clinton signed an immigration law in 1996 that made it easier for the federal government to deport people. The bill also subjected more immigrants to the threat of deportation. But the 1996 immigration law did not lay the groundwork for federal policy that separates children from their parents at the border.

Those claims gave rise to the idea that Bill Clintonâs 1996 immigration law was to blame for the policy. And thatâs not true.

text: But the 1996 law didnât address family separations, or set the stage for them. It established a new asylum status for victims of forced abortion or sterilization. It also required asylum seekers to apply within one year of arrival and denied most re-applicants outright. The law does not require âzero tolerance,â or criminal prosecution of all asylum seekers who cross the border. The law also does not mandate that immigrant children be separated from their family. For those reasons, weâre calling claims that Clintonâs 1996 law is to blame for child separations âfiction.â

text: Although Bill Clinton was president in 1997, he didnât sign the Flores agreement into law. The agreement resulted from a class-action lawsuit that was filed in 1986 byÂ  the Center for Human Rights & Constitutional Law and the National Center for Youth Law, over the treatment of child immigrants in federal facilities.Â  Negotiations and court proceedings dragged on for nine years, spanning three presidencies.
